This is how I would answer it in an MD interview.


---

> My first priority would be customer protection and understanding the scope of the incident.

Even though the breach occurred within the fintech's environment, customers will not distinguish between the fintech and the bank. Their trust in the ecosystem is what is at risk.

Within the first few hours, I would activate the incident response process and establish a cross-functional war room involving security, legal, risk, compliance, communications, and engineering teams.

Next, I would work with the fintech to determine exactly what data was exposed, how many customers were affected, whether the breach is ongoing, and whether access should be suspended immediately.

In parallel, I would assess our contractual obligations, regulatory notification requirements, and customer communication requirements.

Once we have validated facts, I would ensure timely and transparent communication to leadership, regulators where required, partners, and affected customers.

After containment, I would lead a review of what controls failed, whether our onboarding and monitoring processes should change, and whether additional security requirements should be introduced for third-party partners.

Ultimately, my goal is not only to manage the incident but to preserve customer trust. In Open Banking, customers trust us with their financial data, and they expect us to hold partners to the same standards we hold ourselves.




